        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Grace Rectory<lb/>
                Mt Airy Phil&#39;a.<lb/>
                Dec. 18. 1890<lb/></p>
            <p>The Rev Dr Morais.<lb/>
                Rev and Dear Sir.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev Dr Mc Connell alluded<lb/> to the fact of a meeting of<lb/> several persons with you<lb/> when the subject of the<lb/> cruel treatment of the<lb/> Jews in Russia was under<lb/> discussion&#44; after his<lb/> remarks a motion was<lb/> made before the Clerical<lb/> Brotherhood&#44; that the Secretary<lb/> be requested to correspond<lb/> with you and see if you<lb/> and your friend <hi rend="underline">could</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">address</hi> the Brotherhood<lb/> the third Monday in Jan&#44; or<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>any Monday following.<lb/></p>  
            <p>Jan 19th is the first Monday<lb/> we have vacant&#44; or it would<lb/> have been placed at your<lb/> disposal&#44; two weeks ago&#44; a<lb/> resolution had been passed<lb/> adjoining the Brotherhood<lb/> over.  Dec 29. &#38; Jan. 5 and the<lb/> 12 of Jan was engaged&#44; hence<lb/> we have been compelled to<lb/> delay hearing an account<lb/> which I know would touch<lb/> every heart with sympathy.<lb/>  I shall be glad to hear<lb/> from you at your earliest<lb/> convenience&#44; and arrange<lb/> for the meeting.<lb/></p>
            <p>The Clerical Brotherhood<lb/> of the Episcopal Church<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>meets at 15th &#38; Chestnut&#44;<lb/> in the Guild room of the<lb/> Church of the Epiphany&#45;&#45;<lb/> Yours with true sympathy<lb/> S. C. Hill.<lb/> Secretary.<lb/></p>
            <p>P. S.<lb/> I would have come to<lb/> your house and tried to<lb/> arrange this if I were<lb/> not pressed for time and<lb/> living at Mt Airy near<lb/> Chestnut Hill&#44; and do<lb/> not expect to be in the<lb/> city before Monday.<lb/> S. C. H.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
